Merge pull request #855 from patrickhlauke/fix-pan-swipe-touchaction

Fix erroneous `pan-x pan-y` use and handling

make touchaction test zoomable

this helps to test whether `pan-y` works correctly in preventing
horizontal scrolling

do not prevent defaults for `pan-x pan-y` case

`pan-x pan-y` means browser handles all scrolling/panning, do not
prevent these

fix incorrect wording on pan-x pan-y test

`pan-x pan-y` mean that the browser will handle both horizontal and
vertical panning. as such, any custom gesture should *not* be executed
by the script, as the browser will intercept the movement

fix incorrect touch action pan direction

if i want to intercept/handle horizontal pans/swipes, i need `pan-y`,
not `pan-x` (as touch-action determines which default actions the
browser should handle - if i wanted to do my own horizontal pans/swipes,
i DON'T want the browser to handle `pan-x`). the fact that this code
seems to currently work regardless may be due to other logic in the
script, like the part where `touch-action` is combined...

change combined pan-x pan-y to none

if both `pan-x` and `pan-y` are set (different recognizers for different
directions, e.g. horizontal pan but vertical swipe?) we need `none` (as
otherwise with `pan-x pan-y` combined none of these recognizers will
work, since the browser would handle all panning.

Fixing pointer events bug falsely detecting multiple pointers

It is possible for IE to fire a "down" event without a corresponding "up"
event. If this happens, a new "down" event will be falsely added as an
additional pointer. This commit first makes sure the pointer from the
down event is not already in the store before adding it (based on
pointerId).

Merge pull request #330 from cburgdorf/interimDirection

Added interimAngle and interimDirection to event data

Added interimAngle and interimDirection to event data

Currently the angle and the direction are always relative
to the first event. In practice that means, if one drags
100px to the right and then drags 50px back to the left,
the direction still says "right" even so one is actually
dragging to the left.

This commit adds two properties "interimAngle" and
"interimDirection" to the event object which give information
about the angle and direction relative to the last event instead
of relative to the first event.

Merge pull request #216 from rrowland/master

IE10 Multi-touch Gesture Fix

MSPointerMove returns invalid and inconsistent pointer data on the "end" event. For instance, a two-touch event may have pointers 1017 and 1018. When both fingers are released simultaneously, two end events will fire. However,
rather than firing once per event it will fire the same event twice.

We can't reliably remove pointers from our container due to this buggy behavior. Fortunately, MS sends its pointer events constantly as the gesture is held, so there's no need to maintain this list; If we clear the list, it will
be repopulated with a precise and accurate pointer list almost immediately.

Merge pull request #98 from brandonpapworth/patch-1

jquery.specialevent.hammer.js delegate support

jquery.specialevent.hammer.js delegate support

The current implementation does not support using delegated bindings in jQuery, example:
$('ul#root').on('tap','li a button',function(ev){}); // won't fire
This update adds a different method of triggering evens. This method is inherently slower than the current implementation, so a manager has also been added to automatically use the faster, original method over the new, slower, delegate-compatible method.

Merge pull request #90 from michaelpaulson-wf/swipe_fix

Transforming -> swipe
Swipe events were being fired when the transformer was transforming fast.
I followed Mr. Davis's suggested fixes for the _mousedown/drag event being fired.

I have updated the hammer.js file to have Transform to be a higher precedent.  This will require 2 very special considerations.  When a drag to transform is made then there cannot be a 'tap' event.  Hence _can_tap count === 1.  Second, when a second finger enters the scene and the user is in a drag, then a dragEnd must be executed thus the user can take care of any their state information before considering a zoom event (transform).
